:::summary
Dante Alighieri (1265–1321) was the greatest poet of medieval Christendom and, many would argue, of all Western literature — the author of *The Divine Comedy*, a visionary journey through Hell, Purgatory, and Paradise that synthesizes the whole of medieval Christian theology, classical philosophy, and Italian vernacular poetry into a single transcendent masterwork. Guided first by [Virgil](article.html?id=rome) and then by Beatrice, Dante's pilgrim journeys from the depths of sin to the very face of God, and no poem in human history has mapped the spiritual life with greater precision or beauty.
:::

